TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of Ethical Frameworks on Perceptions of Organizational Justice
AU  - Schminke, Marshall
AU  - Ambrose, Maureen L.
AU  - Noel, Terry W.
Y1  - 1997/10/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256932
DO  - 10.5465/256932
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1190
EP  - 1207
VL  - 40
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Research on both ethics and organizational justice distinguishes between process and outcome concerns. However, little research integrates these two areas. This study examined the influence of individuals' ethical frameworks on perceptions of organizational justice. We found that ethical formalists were more sensitive to procedural justice issues and ethical utilitarians were more sensitive to distributive justice issues. The implications of these results for both organizational justice and ethics are discussed.
AB  - Research on both ethics and organizational justice distinguishes between process and outcome concerns. However, little research integrates these two areas. This study examined the influence of individuals' ethical frameworks on perceptions of organizational justice. We found that ethical formalists were more sensitive to procedural justice issues and ethical utilitarians were more sensitive to distributive justice issues. The implications of these results for both organizational justice and ethics are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256932
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256932
Y2  - 2026/04/24
