T1  - The Importance of Collaborative Know-How: An Empirical Test of the Learning Organization
AU  - Simonin, Bernard L.
Y1  - 1997/10/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256930
DO  - 10.5465/256930
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1150
EP  - 1174
VL  - 40
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this research, I proposed and tested a model of how firms learn from their strategic alliances. Based on a survey of 151 firms, the results suggest that experience alone is insufficient for the achievement of the greatest benefits from collaboration. Experience must be internalized first, and collaborative know-how must be developed for this experience to contribute to future collaborative benefits.
AB  - In this research, I proposed and tested a model of how firms learn from their strategic alliances. Based on a survey of 151 firms, the results suggest that experience alone is insufficient for the achievement of the greatest benefits from collaboration. Experience must be internalized first, and collaborative know-how must be developed for this experience to contribute to future collaborative benefits.
