TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Consequences of Employment-Change Decisions in Major U.S. Corporations
AU  - Cascio, Wayne F.
AU  - Young, Clifford E.
AU  - Morris, James R.
Y1  - 1997/10/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256931
DO  - 10.5465/256931
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1175
EP  - 1189
VL  - 40
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Using data from companies in the Standard & Poor's 500 between 1980 and 1994, we examined 5,479 occurrences of changes in employment in terms of two dependent variables: profitability (return on assets) and return on common stock, Firms that engaged in pure employment downsizing did not show significantly higher returns than the average companies in their own industries. However, companies that combined employment downsizing with asset restructuring generated higher returns on assets and stock returns than firms in their own industries.
AB  - Using data from companies in the Standard & Poor's 500 between 1980 and 1994, we examined 5,479 occurrences of changes in employment in terms of two dependent variables: profitability (return on assets) and return on common stock, Firms that engaged in pure employment downsizing did not show significantly higher returns than the average companies in their own industries. However, companies that combined employment downsizing with asset restructuring generated higher returns on assets and stock returns than firms in their own industries.
